# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: model-pruning-ml
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In machine learning, **deep learning** (**DL**) focuses on utilizing multilayered neural networks to perform tasks such as classification, regression, and representation learning.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The field takes inspiration from biological neuroscience and revolves around stacking artificial neurons into layers and "training" them to process data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The adjective "deep" refers to the use of multiple layers (ranging from three to several hundred or thousands) in the network.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Methods used can be supervised, semi-supervised or unsupervised.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Some common deep learning network architectures include fully connected networks, deep belief networks, recurrent neural networks, convolutional neural networks, generative adversarial networks, transformers, and neural radiance fields.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Early forms of neural networks were inspired by information processing and distributed communication nodes in biological systems, particularly the human brain.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] However, current neural networks do not intend to model the brain function of organisms, and are generally seen as low-quality models for that purpose.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Fundamentally, deep learning refers to a class of machine learning algorithms in which a hierarchy of layers is used to transform input data into a progressively more abstract and composite representation.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] For example, in an image recognition model, the raw input may be an image (represented as a tensor of pixels).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The first representational layer may attempt to identify basic shapes such as lines and circles, the second layer may compose and encode arrangements of edges, the third layer may encode a nose and eyes, and the fourth layer may recognize that the image contains a face.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Importantly, a deep learning process can learn which features to optimally place at which level *on its own*.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Prior to deep learning, machine learning techniques often involved hand-crafted feature engineering to transform the data into a more suitable representation for a classification algorithm to operate on.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In the deep learning approach, features are not hand-crafted and the model discovers useful feature representations from the data automatically.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] This does not eliminate the need for hand-tuning; for example, varying numbers of layers and layer sizes can provide different degrees of abstraction.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The word "deep" in "deep learning" refers to the number of layers through which the data is transformed.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] More precisely, deep learning systems have a substantial *credit assignment path* (CAP) depth.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The CAP is the chain of transformations from input to output.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] CAPs describe potentially causal connections between input and output.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] For a feedforward neural network, the depth of the CAPs is that of the network and is the number of hidden layers plus one (as the output layer is also parameterized).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] For recurrent neural networks, in which a signal may propagate through a layer more than once, the CAP depth is potentially unlimited.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] No universally agreed-upon threshold of depth divides shallow learning from deep learning, but most researchers agree that deep learning involves CAP depth higher than two.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] CAP of depth two has been shown to be a universal approximator in the sense that it can emulate any function.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Beyond that, more layers do not add to the function approximator ability of the network.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Deep models (CAP > two) are able to extract better features than shallow models and hence, extra layers help in learning the features effectively.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures can be constructed with a greedy layer-by-layer method.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning helps to disentangle these abstractions and pick out which features improve performance.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms can be applied to unsupervised learning tasks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] This is an important benefit because unlabeled data is more abundant than labeled data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Examples of deep structures that can be trained in an unsupervised manner are deep belief networks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The term *deep learning* was introduced to the machine learning community by Rina Dechter in 1986, and to artificial neural networks by Igor Aizenberg and colleagues in 2000, in the context of Boolean threshold neurons.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The etymology of the term is more complicated.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Deep neural networks are generally interpreted in terms of the universal approximation theorem or probabilistic inference.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The classic universal approximation theorem concerns the capacity of feedforward neural networks with a single hidden layer of finite size to approximate continuous functions.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, the first proof was published by George Cybenko for sigmoid activation functions and was generalised to feed-forward multi-layer architectures in 1991 by Kurt Hornik.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Recent work also showed that universal approximation also holds for non-bounded activation functions such as Kunihiko Fukushima's rectified linear unit.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The universal approximation theorem for deep neural networks concerns the capacity of networks with bounded width but the depth is allowed to grow.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation derives from the field of machine learning.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] It features inference, as well as the optimization concepts of training and testing, related to fitting and generalization, respectively.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] More specifically, the probabilistic interpretation considers the activation nonlinearity as a cumulative distribution function.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation led to the introduction of dropout as regularizer in neural networks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation was introduced by researchers including Hopfield, Widrow and Narendra and popularized in surveys such as the one by Bishop.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] There are two types of artificial neural network (ANN): feedforward neural network (FNN) or multilayer perceptron (MLP) and recurrent neural networks (RNN).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] RNNs have cycles in their connectivity structure, whereas FNNs do not.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In the 1920s, Wilhelm Lenz and Ernst Ising created the Ising model which is essentially a non-learning RNN architecture consisting of neuron-like threshold elements.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari made this architecture adaptive.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] His learning RNN was republished by John Hopfield in 1982.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Other early recurrent neural networks were published by Kaoru Nakano in 1971.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Already in 1948, Alan Turing produced work on "Intelligent Machinery" that was not published in his lifetime, containing "ideas related to artificial evolution and learning RNNs".
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Frank Rosenblatt (1958) proposed the perceptron, an MLP with 3 layers: an input layer, a hidden layer with randomized weights that did not learn, and an output layer.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] He later published a 1962 book that also introduced variants and computer experiments, including a version with four-layer perceptrons "with adaptive preterminal networks" where the last two layers have learned weights (here he credits H.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Joseph (1960) "functionally equivalent to a variation of" this four-layer system (the book mentions Joseph over 30 times).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Should Joseph therefore be considered the originator of proper adaptive multilayer perceptrons with learning hidden units?
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Unfortunately, the learning algorithm was not a functional one, and fell into oblivion.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the Group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Lapa in 1965.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, or a generalization of Rosenblatt's perceptron to handle more complex, nonlinear, and hierarchical relationships.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, which is based on layer by layer training through regression analysis.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Superfluous hidden units are pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Since the activation functions of the nodes are Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, these were also the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tunings have made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the currently dominant training technique.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 1969, Kunihiko Fukushima introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The rectifier has become the most popular activation function for deep learning.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers began with the Neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979, though not trained by backpropagation.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Backpropagation is an efficient application of the chain rule derived by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1673 to networks of differentiable nodes.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was actually introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this, although Henry J.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Kelley had a continuous precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The modern form of backpropagation was first published in Seppo Linnainmaa's master thesis (1970).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Ostrovski et al. republished it in 1971.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not yet describe the algorithm).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Rumelhart et al. popularised backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNN to phoneme recognition.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] It used convolutions, weight sharing, and backpropagation.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to alphabet recognition.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, Yann LeCun et al. created a CNN called LeNet for recognizing handwritten ZIP codes on mail.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 1990, Wei Zhang implemented a CNN on optical computing hardware.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, a CNN was applied to medical image object segmentation and breast cancer detection in mammograms.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al., that classifies digits, was applied by several banks to recognize hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32x32 pixel images.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNN) were further developed in the 1980s.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Recurrence is used for sequence processing, and when a recurrent network is unrolled, it mathematically resembles a deep feedforward layer.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Consequently, they have similar properties and issues, and their developments had mutual influences.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In RNN, two early influential works were the Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990), which applied RNN to study problems in cognitive psychology.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep learning with long credit assignment paths.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] To overcome this problem, in 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed a hierarchy of RNNs pre-trained one level at a time by self-supervised learning where each RNN tries to predict its own next input, which is the next unexpected input of the RNN below.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] This "neural history compressor" uses predictive coding to learn internal representations at multiple self-organizing time scales.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] This can substantially facilitate downstream deep learning.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The RNN hierarchy can be *collapsed* into a single RNN, by distilling a higher level *chunker* network into a lower level *automatizer* network.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The "P" in ChatGPT refers to such pre-training.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis (1991) implemented the neural history compressor, and identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Hochreiter proposed recurrent residual connections to solve the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] This led to the long short-term memory (LSTM), published in 1995.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] LSTM can learn "very deep learning" tasks with long credit assignment paths that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps before.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] That LSTM was not yet the modern architecture, which required a "forget gate", introduced in 1999, which became the standard RNN architecture.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber also published adversarial neural networks that contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The first network is a generative model that models a probability distribution over output patterns.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The second network learns by gradient descent to predict the reactions of the environment to these patterns.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, this principle was used in generative adversarial networks (GANs).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, etc., including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] These were designed for unsupervised learning of deep generative models.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] However, those were more computationally expensive compared to backpropagation.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Boltzmann machine learning algorithm, published in 1985, was briefly popular before being eclipsed by the backpropagation algorithm in 1986.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] A 1988 network became state of the art in protein structure prediction, an early application of deep learning to bioinformatics.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Both shallow and deep learning (e.g., recurrent nets) of ANNs for speech recognition have been explored for many years.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] These methods never outperformed non-uniform internal-handcrafting Gaussian mixture model/Hidden Markov model (GMM-HMM) technology based on generative models of speech trained discriminatively.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Key difficulties have been analyzed, including gradient diminishing and weak temporal correlation structure in neural predictive models.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Additional difficulties were the lack of training data and limited computing power.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Most speech recognition researchers moved away from neural nets to pursue generative modeling.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] An exception was at SRI International in the late 1990s.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Funded by the US government's NSA and DARPA, SRI researched in speech and speaker recognition.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The speaker recognition team led by Larry Heck reported significant success with deep neural networks in speech processing in the 1998 NIST Speaker Recognition benchmark.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] It was deployed in the Nuance Verifier, representing the first major industrial application of deep learning.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The raw features of speech, waveforms, later produced excellent larger-scale results.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2003, LSTM became competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, Alex Graves, Santiago Fernández, Faustino Gomez, and Schmidhuber combined it with connectionist temporal classification (CTC) in stacks of LSTMs.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, it became the first RNN to win a pattern recognition contest, in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, publications by Geoff Hinton, Ruslan Salakhutdinov, Osindero and Teh deep belief networks were developed for generative modeling.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] They are trained by training one restricted Boltzmann machine, then freezing it and training another one on top of the first one, and so on, then optionally fine-tuned using supervised backpropagation.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] They could model high-dimensional probability distributions, such as the distribution of MNIST images, but convergence was slow.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The impact of deep learning in industry began in the early 2000s, when CNNs already processed an estimated 10% to 20% of all the checks written in the US, according to Yann LeCun.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Industrial applications of deep learning to large-scale speech recognition started around 2010.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The 2009 NIPS Workshop on Deep Learning for Speech Recognition was motivated by the limitations of deep generative models of speech, and the possibility that given more capable hardware and large-scale data sets that deep neural nets might become practical.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] It was believed that pre-training DNNs using generative models of deep belief nets (DBN) would overcome the main difficulties of neural nets.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The nature of the recognition errors produced by the two types of systems was characteristically different, offering technical insights into how to integrate deep learning into the existing highly efficient, run-time speech decoding system deployed by all major speech recognition systems.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Analysis around 2009–2010, contrasting the GMM (and other generative speech models) vs.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] DNN models, stimulated early industrial investment in deep learning for speech recognition.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] That analysis was done with comparable performance (less than 1.5% in error rate) between discriminative DNNs and generative models.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2010, researchers extended deep learning from TIMIT to large vocabulary speech recognition, by adopting large output layers of the DNN based on context-dependent HMM states constructed by decision trees.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The deep learning revolution started around CNN- and GPU-based computer vision.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Although CNNs trained by backpropagation had been around for decades and GPU implementations of NNs for years, including CNNs, faster implementations of CNNs on GPUs were needed to progress on computer vision.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Later, as deep learning becomes widespread, specialized hardware and algorithm optimizations were developed specifically for deep learning.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] A key advance for the deep learning revolution was hardware advances, especially GPU.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, Raina, Madhavan, and Andrew Ng reported a 100M deep belief network trained on 30 Nvidia GeForce GTX 280 GPUs, an early demonstration of GPU-based deep learning.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] They reported up to 70 times faster training.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2011, a CNN named *DanNet* by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Jürgen Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance significantly.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2012, Andrew Ng and Jeff Dean created an FNN that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, only from watching unlabeled images taken from YouTube videos.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Geoffrey Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Further incremental improvements included the VGG-16 network by Karen Simonyan and Andrew Zisserman and Google's Inceptionv3.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The success in image classification was then extended to the more challenging task of generating descriptions (captions) for images, often as a combination of CNNs and LSTMs.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Stacking too many layers led to a steep reduction in training accuracy, known as the "degradation" problem.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, two techniques were developed to train very deep networks: the highway network was published in May 2015, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in Dec 2015.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] ResNet behaves like an open-gated Highway Net.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Around the same time, deep learning started impacting the field of art.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Early examples included Google DeepDream (2015), and neural style transfer (2015), both of which were based on pretrained image classification neural networks, such as VGG-19.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Generative adversarial network (GAN) by (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) (based on Jürgen Schmidhuber's principle of artificial curiosity) became state of the art in generative modeling during 2014-2018 period.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Excellent image quality is achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Here the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Image generation by GAN reached popular success, and provoked discussions concerning deepfakes.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling since then, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, Google's speech recognition improved by 49% by an LSTM-based model, which they made available through Google Voice Search on smartphone.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning is part of state-of-the-art systems in various disciplines, particularly computer vision and automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Results on commonly used evaluation sets such as TIMIT (ASR) and MNIST (image classification), as well as a range of large-vocabulary speech recognition tasks have steadily improved.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks were superseded for ASR by LSTM. but are more successful in computer vision.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Yoshua Bengio, Geoffrey Hinton and Yann LeCun were awarded the 2018 Turing Award for "conceptual and engineering breakthroughs that have made deep neural networks a critical component of computing".
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] An ANN is based on a collection of connected units called artificial neurons, (analogous to biological neurons in a biological brain).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Each connection (synapse) between neurons can transmit a signal to another neuron.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The receiving (postsynaptic) neuron can process the signal(s) and then signal downstream neurons connected to it.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Neurons may have state, generally represented by real numbers, typically between 0 and 1.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Neurons and synapses may also have a weight that varies as learning proceeds, which can increase or decrease the strength of the signal that it sends downstream.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Typically, neurons are organized in layers.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first (input), to the last (output) layer, possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The original goal of the neural network approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Over time, attention focused on matching specific mental abilities, leading to deviations from biology such as backpropagation, or passing information in the reverse direction and adjusting the network to reflect that information.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] As of 2017, neural networks typically have a few thousand to a few million units and millions of connections.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Despite this number being several order of magnitude less than the number of neurons on a human brain, these networks can perform many tasks at a level beyond that of humans (e.g., recognizing faces, or playing "Go").
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] A **deep neural network** (**DNN**) is an artificial neural network with multiple layers between the input and output layers.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] There are different types of neural networks but they always consist of the same components: neurons, synapses, weights, biases, and functions.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] These components as a whole function in a way that mimics functions of the human brain, and can be trained like any other ML algorithm.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] For example, a DNN that is trained to recognize dog breeds will go over the given image and calculate the probability that the dog in the image is a certain breed.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The user can review the results and select which probabilities the network should display (above a certain threshold, etc.) and return the proposed label.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Each mathematical manipulation as such is considered a layer, and complex DNN have many layers, hence the name "deep" networks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] DNNs can model complex non-linear relationships.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] DNN architectures generate compositional models where the object is expressed as a layered composition of primitives.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The extra layers enable composition of features from lower layers, potentially modeling complex data with fewer units than a similarly performing shallow network.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] For instance, it was proved that sparse multivariate polynomials are exponentially easier to approximate with DNNs than with shallow networks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Deep architectures include many variants of a few basic approaches.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Each architecture has found success in specific domains.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] It is not always possible to compare the performance of multiple architectures, unless they have been evaluated on the same data sets.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are typically feedforward networks in which data flows from the input layer to the output layer without looping back.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] At first, the DNN creates a map of virtual neurons and assigns random numerical values, or "weights", to connections between them.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The weights and inputs are multiplied and return an output between 0 and 1.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] If the network did not accurately recognize a particular pattern, an algorithm would adjust the weights.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] That way the algorithm can make certain parameters more influential, until it determines the correct mathematical manipulation to fully process the data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks, in which data can flow in any direction, are used for applications such as language modeling.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Long short-term memory is particularly effective for this use.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are used in computer vision.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] CNNs also have been applied to acoustic modeling for automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] As with ANNs, many issues can arise with naively trained DNNs.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Two common issues are overfitting and computation time.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are prone to overfitting because of the added layers of abstraction, which allow them to model rare dependencies in the training data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Regularization methods such as Ivakhnenko's unit pruning or weight decay ( $\ell _{2}$ -regularization) or sparsity ( $\ell _{1}$ -regularization) can be applied during training to combat overfitting.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively dropout regularization randomly omits units from the hidden layers during training.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] This helps to exclude rare dependencies.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Another interesting recent development is research into models of just enough complexity through an estimation of the intrinsic complexity of the task being modelled.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] This approach has been successfully applied for multivariate time series prediction tasks such as traffic prediction.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Finally, data can be augmented via methods such as cropping and rotating such that smaller training sets can be increased in size to reduce the chances of overfitting.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] DNNs must consider many training parameters, such as the size (number of layers and number of units per layer), the learning rate, and initial weights.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Sweeping through the parameter space for optimal parameters may not be feasible due to the cost in time and computational resources.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Various tricks, such as batching (computing the gradient on several training examples at once rather than individual examples) speed up computation.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Large processing capabilities of many-core architectures (such as GPUs or the Intel Xeon Phi) have produced significant speedups in training, because of the suitability of such processing architectures for the matrix and vector computations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively, engineers may look for other types of neural networks with more straightforward and convergent training algorithms.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] CMAC (cerebellar model articulation controller) is one such kind of neural network.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] It doesn't require learning rates or randomized initial weights.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The training process can be guaranteed to converge in one step with a new batch of data, and the computational complexity of the training algorithm is linear with respect to the number of neurons involved.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks that contain many layers of non-linear hidden units and a very large output layer.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method for training large-scale commercial cloud AI .
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] OpenAI estimated the hardware computation used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017) and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of computation required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Special electronic circuits called deep learning processors were designed to speed up deep learning algorithms.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning processors include neural processing units (NPUs) in Huawei cellphones and cloud computing servers such as tensor processing units (TPU) in the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Cerebras Systems has also built a dedicated system to handle large deep learning models, the CS-2, based on the largest processor in the industry, the second-generation Wafer Scale Engine (WSE-2).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Atomically thin semiconductors are considered promising for energy-efficient deep learning hardware where the same basic device structure is used for both logic operations and data storage.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] In 2020, Marega et al. published experiments with a large-area active channel material for developing logic-in-memory devices and circuits based on floating-gate field-effect transistors (FGFETs).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Feldmann et al. proposed an integrated photonic hardware accelerator for parallel convolutional processing.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] The authors identify two key advantages of integrated photonics over its electronic counterparts: (1) massively parallel data transfer through wavelength division multiplexing in conjunction with frequency combs, and (2) extremely high data modulation speeds.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p01] Their system can execute trillions of multiply-accumulate operations per second, indicating the potential of integrated photonics in data-heavy AI applications.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Large-scale automatic speech recognition is the first and most convincing successful case of deep learning.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] LSTM RNNs can learn "Very Deep Learning" tasks that involve multi-second intervals containing speech events separated by thousands of discrete time steps, where one time step corresponds to about 10 ms.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] LSTM with forget gates is competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The initial success in speech recognition was based on small-scale recognition tasks based on TIMIT.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The data set contains 630 speakers from eight major dialects of American English, where each speaker reads 10 sentences.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Its small size lets many configurations be tried.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] More importantly, the TIMIT task concerns phone-sequence recognition, which, unlike word-sequence recognition, allows weak phone bigram language models.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] This lets the strength of the acoustic modeling aspects of speech recognition be more easily analyzed.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The error rates listed below, including these early results and measured as percent phone error rates (PER), have been summarized since 1991.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] More recent speech recognition models use Transformers or Temporal Convolution Networks with significant success and widespread applications.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] All major commercial speech recognition systems (e.g., Microsoft Cortana, Xbox, Skype Translator, Amazon Alexa, Google Now, Apple Siri, Baidu and iFlyTek voice search, and a range of Nuance speech products, etc.) are based on deep learning.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] A common evaluation set for image classification is the MNIST database data set.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] MNIST is composed of handwritten digits and includes 60,000 training examples and 10,000 test examples.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] As with TIMIT, its small size lets users test multiple configurations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] A comprehensive list of results on this set is available.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-based image recognition has become "superhuman", producing more accurate results than human contestants.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] This first occurred in 2011 in recognition of traffic signs, and in 2014, with recognition of human faces.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-trained vehicles now interpret 360° camera views.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Another example is Facial Dysmorphology Novel Analysis (FDNA) used to analyze cases of human malformation connected to a large database of genetic syndromes.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Closely related to the progress that has been made in image recognition is the increasing application of deep learning techniques to various visual art tasks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Neural networks have been used for implementing language models since the early 2000s.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] LSTM helped to improve machine translation and language modeling.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Other key techniques in this field are negative sampling and word embedding.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Word embedding, such as *word2vec*, can be thought of as a representational layer in a deep learning architecture that transforms an atomic word into a positional representation of the word relative to other words in the dataset; the position is represented as a point in a vector space.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Using word embedding as an RNN input layer allows the network to parse sentences and phrases using an effective compositional vector grammar.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] A compositional vector grammar can be thought of as probabilistic context free grammar (PCFG) implemented by an RNN.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Recursive auto-encoders built atop word embeddings can assess sentence similarity and detect paraphrasing.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Recent developments generalize word embedding to sentence embedding.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate (GT) uses a large end-to-end long short-term memory (LSTM) network.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Google Neural Machine Translation (GNMT) uses an example-based machine translation method in which the system "learns from millions of examples".
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] It translates "whole sentences at a time, rather than pieces".
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate supports over one hundred languages.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The network encodes the "semantics of the sentence rather than simply memorizing phrase-to-phrase translations".
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] GT uses English as an intermediate between most language pairs.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] A large percentage of candidate drugs fail to win regulatory approval.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] These failures are caused by insufficient efficacy (on-target effect), undesired interactions (off-target effects), or unanticipated toxic effects.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Research has explored use of deep learning to predict the biomolecular targets, off-targets, and toxic effects of environmental chemicals in nutrients, household products and drugs.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet is a deep learning system for structure-based rational drug design.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for disease targets such as the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 graph neural networks were used for the first time to predict various properties of molecules in a large toxicology data set.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In 2019, generative neural networks were used to produce molecules that were validated experimentally all the way into mice.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Recommendation systems have used deep learning to extract meaningful features for a latent factor model for content-based music and journal recommendations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Multi-view deep learning has been applied for learning user preferences from multiple domains.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The model uses a hybrid collaborative and content-based approach and enhances recommendations in multiple tasks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] An autoencoder ANN was used in bioinformatics, to predict gene ontology annotations and gene-function relationships.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In medical informatics, deep learning was used to predict sleep quality based on data from wearables and predictions of health complications from electronic health record data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks have shown unparalleled performance in predicting protein structure, according to the sequence of the amino acids that make it up.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In 2020, AlphaFold, a deep-learning based system, achieved a level of accuracy significantly higher than all previous computational methods.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks can be used to estimate the entropy of a stochastic process through an arrangement called a Neural Joint Entropy Estimator (NJEE).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Such an estimation provides insights on the effects of input random variables on an independent random variable.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Practically, the DNN is trained as a classifier that maps an input vector or matrix X to an output probability distribution over the possible classes of random variable Y, given input X.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] For example, in image classification tasks, the NJEE maps a vector of pixels' color values to probabilities over possible image classes.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In practice, the probability distribution of Y is obtained by a Softmax layer with number of nodes that is equal to the alphabet size of Y.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] NJEE uses continuously differentiable activation functions, such that the conditions for the universal approximation theorem holds.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] It is shown that this method provides a strongly consistent estimator and outperforms other methods in cases of large alphabet sizes.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been shown to produce competitive results in medical applications such as cancer cell classification, lesion detection, organ segmentation and image enhancement.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Modern deep learning tools demonstrate the high accuracy of detecting various diseases and the helpfulness of their use by specialists to improve the diagnosis efficiency.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Finding the appropriate mobile audience for mobile advertising is always challenging, since many data points must be considered and analyzed before a target segment can be created and used in ad serving by any ad server.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been used to interpret large, many-dimensioned advertising datasets.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Many data points are collected during the request/serve/click internet advertising cycle.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] This information can form the basis of machine learning to improve ad selection.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been successfully applied to inverse problems such as denoising, super-resolution, inpainting, and film colorization.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] These applications include learning methods such as "Shrinkage Fields for Effective Image Restoration" which trains on an image dataset, and Deep Image Prior, which trains on the image that needs restoration.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is being applied to financial fraud detection, tax evasion detection, and anti-money laundering.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In November 2023, researchers at Google DeepMind and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced that they had developed an AI system known as GNoME.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] This system has contributed to materials science by discovering over 2 million new materials within a relatively short timeframe.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] GNoME employs deep learning techniques to efficiently explore potential material structures, achieving a significant increase in the identification of stable inorganic crystal structures.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The system's predictions were validated through autonomous robotic experiments, demonstrating a noteworthy success rate of 71%.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The data of newly discovered materials is publicly available through the Materials Project database, offering researchers the opportunity to identify materials with desired properties for various applications.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] This development has implications for the future of scientific discovery and the integration of AI in material science research, potentially expediting material innovation and reducing costs in product development.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The use of AI and deep learning suggests the possibility of minimizing or eliminating manual lab experiments and allowing scientists to focus more on the design and analysis of unique compounds.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The United States Department of Defense applied deep learning to train robots in new tasks through observation.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Physics-informed neural networks have been used to solve partial differential equations in both forward and inverse problems in a data driven manner.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] One example is the reconstructing fluid flow governed by the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Using physics informed neural networks does not require the often expensive mesh generation that conventional CFD methods rely on.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] It is evident that geometric and physical constraints have a synergistic effect on neural PDE surrogates, thereby enhancing their efficacy in predicting stable and super long rollouts.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep backward stochastic differential equation method is a numerical method that combines deep learning with Backward stochastic differential equation (BSDE).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] This method is particularly useful for solving high-dimensional problems in financial mathematics.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] By leveraging the powerful function approximation capabilities of deep neural networks, deep BSDE addresses the computational challenges faced by traditional numerical methods in high-dimensional settings.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Specifically, traditional methods like finite difference methods or Monte Carlo simulations often struggle with the curse of dimensionality, where computational cost increases exponentially with the number of dimensions.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep BSDE methods, however, employ deep neural networks to approximate solutions of high-dimensional partial differential equations (PDEs), effectively reducing the computational burden.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In addition, the integration of Physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) into the deep BSDE framework enhances its capability by embedding the underlying physical laws directly into the neural network architecture.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] This ensures that the solutions not only fit the data but also adhere to the governing stochastic differential equations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] PINNs leverage the power of deep learning while respecting the constraints imposed by the physical models, resulting in more accurate and reliable solutions for financial mathematics problems.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Image reconstruction is the reconstruction of the underlying images from the image-related measurements.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Several works showed the better and superior performance of the deep learning methods compared to analytical methods for various applications, e.g., spectral imaging and ultrasound imaging.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Traditional weather prediction systems solve a very complex system of partial differential equations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] GraphCast is a deep learning based model, trained on a long history of weather data to predict how weather patterns change over time.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] It is able to predict weather conditions for up to 10 days globally, at a very detailed level, and in under a minute, with precision similar to state of the art systems.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] An epigenetic clock is a biochemical test that can be used to measure age.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Galkin et al. used deep neural networks to train an epigenetic aging clock of unprecedented accuracy using >6,000 blood samples.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The clock uses information from 1000 CpG sites and predicts people with certain conditions older than healthy controls: IBD, frontotemporal dementia, ovarian cancer, obesity.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The aging clock was planned to be released for public use in 2021 by an Insilico Medicine spinoff company Deep Longevity.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is closely related to a class of theories of brain development (specifically, neocortical development) proposed by cognitive neuroscientists in the early 1990s.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] These developmental theories were instantiated in computational models, making them predecessors of deep learning systems.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] These developmental models share the property that various proposed learning dynamics in the brain (e.g., a wave of nerve growth factor) support the self-organization somewhat analogous to the neural networks utilized in deep learning models.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Like the neocortex, neural networks employ a hierarchy of layered filters in which each layer considers information from a prior layer (or the operating environment), and then passes its output (and possibly the original input), to other layers.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] This process yields a self-organizing stack of transducers, well-tuned to their operating environment.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] A 1995 description stated, "...the infant's brain seems to organize itself under the influence of waves of so-called trophic-factors ... different regions of the brain become connected sequentially, with one layer of tissue maturing before another and so on until the whole brain is mature".
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] A variety of approaches have been used to investigate the plausibility of deep learning models from a neurobiological perspective.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] On the one hand, several variants of the backpropagation algorithm have been proposed in order to increase its processing realism.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Other researchers have argued that unsupervised forms of deep learning, such as those based on hierarchical generative models and deep belief networks, may be closer to biological reality.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In this respect, generative neural network models have been related to neurobiological evidence about sampling-based processing in the cerebral cortex.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Although a systematic comparison between the human brain organization and the neuronal encoding in deep networks has not yet been established, several analogies have been reported.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] For example, the computations performed by deep learning units could be similar to those of actual neurons and neural populations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Similarly, the representations developed by deep learning models are similar to those measured in the primate visual system both at the single-unit and at the population levels.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Facebook's AI lab performs tasks such as automatically tagging uploaded pictures with the names of the people in them.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Google's DeepMind Technologies developed a system capable of learning how to play Atari video games using only pixels as data input.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In 2015 they demonstrated their AlphaGo system, which learned the game of Go well enough to beat a professional Go player.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate uses a neural network to translate between more than 100 languages.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In 2017, Covariant.ai was launched, which focuses on integrating deep learning into factories.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] First developed as TAMER, a new algorithm called Deep TAMER was later introduced in 2018 during a collaboration between U.S.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) and UT researchers.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep TAMER used deep learning to provide a robot with the ability to learn new tasks through observation.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Using Deep TAMER, a robot learned a task with a human trainer, watching video streams or observing a human perform a task in-person.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The robot later practiced the task with the help of some coaching from the trainer, who provided feedback such as "good job" and "bad job".
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has attracted both criticism and comment, in some cases from outside the field of computer science.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] A main criticism concerns the lack of theory surrounding some methods.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Learning in the most common deep architectures is implemented using well-understood gradient descent.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] However, the theory surrounding other algorithms, such as contrastive divergence is less clear.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] What is it approximating?) Deep learning methods are often looked at as a black box, with most confirmations done empirically, rather than theoretically.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] With the support of Innovation Diffusion Theory (IDT), a study analyzed the diffusion of deep learning in BRICS and OECD countries using data from Google Trends.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Some deep learning architectures display problematic behaviors, such as confidently classifying unrecognizable images as belonging to a familiar category of ordinary images (2014) and misclassifying minuscule perturbations of correctly classified images (2013).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Goertzel hypothesized that these behaviors are due to limitations in their internal representations and that these limitations would inhibit integration into heterogeneous multi-component artificial general intelligence (AGI) architectures.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] These issues may possibly be addressed by deep learning architectures that internally form states homologous to image-grammar decompositions of observed entities and events.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Learning a grammar (visual or linguistic) from training data would be equivalent to restricting the system to commonsense reasoning that operates on concepts in terms of grammatical production rules and is a basic goal of both human language acquisition and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] As deep learning moves from the lab into the world, research and experience show that artificial neural networks are vulnerable to hacks and deception.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] By identifying patterns that these systems use to function, attackers can modify inputs to ANNs in such a way that the ANN finds a match that human observers would not recognize.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] For example, an attacker can make subtle changes to an image such that the ANN finds a match even though the image looks to a human nothing like the search target.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Such manipulation is termed an "adversarial attack".
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In 2016 researchers used one ANN to doctor images in trial and error fashion, identify another's focal points, and thereby generate images that deceived it.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The modified images looked no different to human eyes.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that printouts of doctored images then photographed successfully tricked an image classification system.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] One defense is reverse image search, in which a possible fake image is submitted to a site such as TinEye that can then find other instances of it.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that certain psychedelic spectacles could fool a facial recognition system into thinking ordinary people were celebrities, potentially allowing one person to impersonate another.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 researchers added stickers to stop signs and caused an ANN to misclassify them.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] ANNs can however be further trained to detect attempts at deception, potentially leading attackers and defenders into an arms race similar to the kind that already defines the malware defense industry.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] ANNs have been trained to defeat ANN-based anti-malware software by repeatedly attacking a defense with malware that was continually altered by a genetic algorithm until it tricked the anti-malware while retaining its ability to damage the target.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In 2016, another group demonstrated that certain sounds could make the Google Now voice command system open a particular web address, and hypothesized that this could "serve as a stepping stone for further attacks (e.g., opening a web page hosting drive-by malware)".
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] In "data poisoning", false data is continually smuggled into a machine learning system's training set to prevent it from achieving mastery.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The deep learning systems that are trained using supervised learning often rely on data that is created or annotated by humans, or both.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] It has been argued that not only low-paid clickwork (such as on Amazon Mechanical Turk) is regularly deployed for this purpose, but also implicit forms of human microwork that are often not recognized as such.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] The philosopher Rainer Mühlhoff distinguishes five types of "machinic capture" of human microwork to generate training data: (1) gamification (the embedding of annotation or computation tasks in the flow of a game), (2) "trapping and tracking" (e.g.
[src:model-pruning-ml/deep-learning-p02] CAPTCHAs for image recognition or click-tracking on Google search results pages), (3) exploitation of social motivations (e.g. tagging faces on Facebook to obtain labeled facial images), (4) information mining (e.g. by leveraging quantified-self devices such as activity trackers) and (5) clickwork.
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] In machine learning, the **lottery ticket hypothesis** is that artificial neural networks with random weights can contain a subnetwork which (entirely by chance) can be tuned to a similar performance as tuning the whole network.
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] Train for j iterations → weights $\theta _{j}$ .
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] Magnitude pruning: build a bitmask m by setting to 0 the lowest-magnitude weights in each layer (one-shot), or repeat train → prune across rounds to reach higher sparsity (iterative).
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] Reset surviving weights to initialization: use $m\odot \theta _{0}$ as the starting point.
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] Here $\odot$ is elementwise multiplication.
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] Train the masked network $f\!\left(x;m\odot \theta _{0}\right)$ with the same optimizer, schedule, and data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] Declare "winning ticket" if it achieves comparable test accuracy in $\leq j$ iterations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] Such networks are a priori difficult to find, since before training, one does not know which of the exponentially many subnetwork would be "lottery tickets".
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] However, after training, these lottery tickets can be discovered by the pruning algorithm.
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] It was found that during the original training of the initial dense network, the weights that would end up in the winning ticket change a lot, but the other weights change little.
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] It was found that if instead of $m\odot \theta _{0}$ , they re-sampled a different random initialization $\theta _{0}'$ , and used $m\odot \theta _{0}'$ instead, the trained $f\!\left(x;m\odot \theta _{0}'\right)$ would perform much worse.
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] This indicates that what makes a ticket winning is both its connection graph and the precise initial weights of the connections.
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] Malach *et al.* proved a stronger version of the hypothesis, namely that a sufficiently overparameterized untuned network will typically contain a subnetwork that is *already* an approximation to the given goal, even before tuning.
[src:model-pruning-ml/lottery-ticket-hypothesis] A similar result has been proven for the special case of convolutional neural networks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Compressed models enable deployment on resource-constrained devices such as smartphones, embedded systems, edge computing devices, and consumer electronics computers.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Efficient inference is also valuable for large corporations that serve large model inference over an API, allowing them to reduce computational costs and improve response times for users.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Model compression is not to be confused with knowledge distillation, in which a smaller "student" model is *trained* to imitate the input-output behavior of a larger "teacher" model (as opposed to using the "teacher"'s trained parameters or the "teacher"'s training targets).
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Several techniques are employed for model compression.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Pruning sparsifies a large model by setting some parameters to exactly zero.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] This effectively reduces the number of parameters.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] This allows the use of sparse matrix operations, which are faster than dense matrix operations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Pruning criteria can be based on magnitudes of parameters, the statistical pattern of neural activations, Hessian values, etc.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Quantization reduces the numerical precision of weights and activations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] For example, instead of storing weights as 32-bit floating-point numbers, they can be represented using 8-bit integers.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Low-precision parameters take up less space, and takes less compute to perform arithmetic with.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] It is also possible to quantize some parameters more aggressively than others, so for example, a less important parameter can have 8-bit precision while another, more important parameter, can have 16-bit precision.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Inference with such models requires mixed-precision arithmetic.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Quantized models can also be used during training (rather than after training).
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] PyTorch implements automatic mixed-precision (AMP), which performs autocasting, gradient scaling, and loss scaling.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Weight matrices can be approximated by low-rank matrices.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Let W be a weight matrix of shape $m\times n$ .
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] A low-rank approximation is $W\approx UV^{T}$ , where U and V are matrices of shapes $m\times k,n\times k$ .
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] When k is small, this both reduces the number of parameters needed to represent W approximately, and accelerates matrix multiplication by W .
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Low-rank approximations can be found by singular value decomposition (SVD).
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] The choice of rank for each weight matrix is a hyperparameter, and jointly optimized as a mixed discrete-continuous optimization problem.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] The rank of weight matrices may also be pruned after training, taking into account the effect of activation functions like ReLU on the implicit rank of the weight matrices.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] Model compression may be decoupled from training, that is, a model is first trained without regard for how it might be compressed, then it is compressed.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] However, it may also be combined with training.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] The "train big, then compress" method trains a large model for a small number of training steps (less than it would be if it were trained to convergence), then heavily compress the model.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] It is found that at the same compute budget, this method results in a better model than lightly compressed, small models.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] In Deep Compression, the compression has three steps.
[src:model-pruning-ml/model-compression] The SqueezeNet paper reported that Deep Compression achieved a compression ratio of 35 on AlexNet, and a ratio of ~10 on SqueezeNets.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] In mathematical modeling, **overfitting** is the production of an analysis that corresponds too closely or exactly to a particular set of data, and may therefore fail to fit to additional data or predict future observations reliably.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] An **overfitted model** is a mathematical model that contains more parameters than can be justified by the data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] In the special case of a model that consists of a polynomial function, these parameters represent the degree of a polynomial.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] The essence of overfitting is to unknowingly extract some of the residual variation (i.e., noise) as if that variation represents the underlying model structure.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] The possibility of over-fitting exists when the criterion used for selecting the model is not the same as the criterion used to judge the suitability of a model.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] As an extreme example, if the number of parameters is the same as or greater than the number of observations, then a model can perfectly predict the training data simply by memorizing the data in its entirety.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] (For an illustration, see Figure 2.) Such a model will typically fail severely when making predictions.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Overfitting is related to both the complexity of the chosen model and how well it is optimized during training.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] A function class that is too large, in a suitable sense, relative to the dataset size is likely to overfit.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Even when the fitted model does not have an excessive number of parameters, it is to be expected that the fitted relationship will appear to perform less well on a new dataset than on the dataset used for fitting (a phenomenon sometimes known as *shrinkage*).
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] In particular, the value of the coefficient of determination will shrink relative to the original data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] To lessen the chance or amount of overfitting, several techniques are available (e.g., model comparison, cross-validation, regularization, early stopping, pruning, Bayesian priors, or dropout).
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] The basis of some techniques is to either (1) explicitly penalize overly complex models or (2) test the model's ability to generalize by evaluating its performance on a set of data not used for training, which is assumed to approximate the typical unseen data that a model will encounter.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] In statistics, an inference is drawn from a statistical model, which has been selected via some procedure.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Burnham & Anderson, in their much-cited text on model selection, argue that to avoid overfitting, one should adhere to the "Principle of Parsimony".
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Overfitting is more likely to be a serious concern when there is little theory available to guide the analysis, in part because then there tend to be a large number of models to select from.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] The book *Model Selection and Model Averaging* (2008) puts it this way.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] In regression analysis, overfitting occurs frequently.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] As an extreme example, if there are *p* variables in a linear regression with *p* data points, the fitted line can go exactly through every point.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] For logistic regression or Cox proportional hazards models, there are a variety of rules of thumb (e.g.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] 5–9, 10 and 10–15 — the guideline of 10 observations per independent variable is known as the "one in ten rule").
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] In the process of regression model selection, the mean squared error of the random regression function can be split into random noise, approximation bias, and variance in the estimate of the regression function.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] The bias–variance tradeoff is often used to overcome overfit models.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] With a large set of explanatory variables that actually have no relation to the dependent variable being predicted, some variables will in general be falsely found to be statistically significant and the researcher may thus retain them in the model, thereby overfitting the model.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Usually, a learning algorithm is trained using some set of "training data": exemplary situations for which the desired output is known.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] The goal is that the algorithm will also perform well on predicting the output when fed "validation data" that was not encountered during its training.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Overfitting is the use of models or procedures that violate Occam's razor, for example by including more adjustable parameters than are ultimately optimal, or by using a more complicated approach than is ultimately optimal.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] For an example where there are too many adjustable parameters, consider a dataset where training data for y can be adequately predicted by a linear function of two independent variables.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Such a function requires only three parameters (the intercept and two slopes).
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Replacing this simple function with a new, more complex quadratic function, or with a new, more complex linear function on more than two independent variables, carries a risk: Occam's razor implies that any given complex function is *a priori* less probable than any given simple function.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] When comparing different types of models, complexity cannot be measured solely by counting how many parameters exist in each model; the expressivity of each parameter must be considered as well.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] For example, it is nontrivial to directly compare the complexity of a neural net (which can track curvilinear relationships) with m parameters to a regression model with n parameters.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Overfitting is especially likely in cases where learning was performed too long or where training examples are rare, causing the learner to adjust to very specific random features of the training data that have no causal relation to the target function.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] In this process of overfitting, the performance on the training examples still increases while the performance on unseen data becomes worse.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] As a simple example, consider a database of retail purchases that includes the item bought, the purchaser, and the date and time of purchase.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] It's easy to construct a model that will fit the training set perfectly by using the date and time of purchase to predict the other attributes, but this model will not generalize at all to new data because those past times will never occur again.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Generally, a learning algorithm is said to overfit relative to a simpler one if it is more accurate in fitting known data (hindsight) but less accurate in predicting new data (foresight).
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] One can intuitively understand overfitting from the fact that information from all past experience can be divided into two groups: information that is relevant for the future, and irrelevant information ("noise").
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Everything else being equal, the more difficult a criterion is to predict (i.e., the higher its uncertainty), the more noise exists in past information that needs to be ignored.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] The problem is determining which part to ignore.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] may produce outputs that are virtually identical to instances from their training set.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] The most obvious consequence of overfitting is poor performance on the validation dataset.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] The optimal function usually needs verification on bigger or completely new datasets.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] There are, however, methods like minimum spanning tree or life-time of correlation that applies the dependence between correlation coefficients and time-series (window width).
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Whenever the window width is big enough, the correlation coefficients are stable and don't depend on the window width size anymore.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Therefore, a correlation matrix can be created by calculating a coefficient of correlation between investigated variables.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] This matrix can be represented topologically as a complex network where direct and indirect influences between variables are visualized.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Dropout regularisation (random removal of training set data) can also improve robustness and therefore reduce over-fitting by probabilistically removing inputs to a layer.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Pruning is another technique that mitigates overfitting and enhances generalization by identifying a sparse, optimal neural network structure, while simultaneously reducing the computational cost of both training and inference.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Underfitting is the inverse of overfitting, meaning that the statistical model or machine learning algorithm is too simplistic to accurately capture the patterns in the data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] A sign of underfitting is that there is a high bias and low variance detected in the current model or algorithm used (the inverse of overfitting: low bias and high variance).
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] This can be gathered from the Bias-variance tradeoff, which is the method of analyzing a model or algorithm for bias error, variance error, and irreducible error.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] With a high bias and low variance, the result of the model is that it will inaccurately represent the data points and thus insufficiently be able to predict future data results (see Generalization error).
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] As shown in Figure 5, the linear line could not represent all the given data points due to the line not resembling the curvature of the points.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] One would expect to see a parabola-shaped line as shown in Figure 6 and Figure 1.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] If Figure 5 were to be used for analysis, false predictive results would be given contrary to the results if Figure 6 was analyzed.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Use a different algorithm: If the current algorithm is not able to capture the patterns in the data, it may be necessary to try a different one.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] For example, a neural network may be more effective than a linear regression model for some types of data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Increase the amount of training data: If the model is underfitting due to a lack of data, increasing the amount of training data may help.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] This will allow the model to better capture the underlying patterns in the data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Regularization: Regularization is a technique used to prevent overfitting by adding a penalty term to the loss function that discourages large parameter values.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] It can also be used to prevent underfitting by controlling the complexity of the model.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Ensemble Methods: Ensemble methods combine multiple models to create a more accurate prediction.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] This can help reduce underfitting by allowing multiple models to work together to capture the underlying patterns in the data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Feature engineering: Feature engineering involves creating new model features from the existing ones that may be more relevant to the problem at hand.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] This can help improve the accuracy of the model and prevent underfitting.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] Benign overfitting describes the phenomenon of a statistical model that seems to generalize well to unseen data, even when it has been fit perfectly on noisy training data (i.e., obtains perfect predictive accuracy on the training set).
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] The phenomenon is of particular interest in deep neural networks, but is studied from a theoretical perspective in the context of much simpler models, such as linear regression.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] In particular, it has been shown that overparameterization is essential for benign overfitting in this setting.
[src:model-pruning-ml/overfitting] In other words, the number of directions in parameter space that are unimportant for prediction must significantly exceed the sample size.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] In deep learning, **pruning** is the practice of removing parameters from an existing artificial neural network.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] The goal of this process is to reduce the size (parameter count) of the neural network (and therefore the computational resources required to run it) whilst maintaining accuracy.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] This can be compared to the biological process of synaptic pruning which takes place in mammalian brains during development.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Rank the neurons according to their importance (assuming there is a clearly defined measure for "importance").
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Check a termination condition (to be determined by the user) to see whether to continue pruning.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Most work on neural network pruning does not remove full neurons or layers (structured pruning).
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Instead, it focuses on removing the most insignificant weights (unstructured pruning), namely, setting their values to zero.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] This can either be done globally by comparing weights from all layers in the network or locally by comparing weights in each layer separately.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Different metrics can be used to measure the importance of each weight.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Weight magnitude as well as combinations of weight and gradient information are commonly used metrics.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Early work suggested also to change the values of non-pruned weights.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Pruning can be applied at three different stages: before training, during training, or after training.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] When pruning is performed during or after training, additional fine-tuning epochs are typically required.
[src:model-pruning-ml/pruning-artificial-neural-network] Each approach involves different trade-offs between accuracy and computational cost.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] In mathematics, statistics, finance, and computer science, particularly in machine learning and inverse problems, **regularization** is a process that converts the answer to a problem to a simpler one.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] It is often used in solving ill-posed problems or to prevent overfitting.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] There is a strong connection between regularization methods and Bayesian approaches for solving such ill-posed problems .
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] In explicit regularization, independent of the problem or model, there is always a data term, that corresponds to a likelihood of the measurement, and a regularization term that corresponds to a prior.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] By combining both using Bayesian statistics, one can compute a posterior, that includes both information sources and therefore stabilizes the estimation process.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] By trading off both objectives, one chooses to be more aligned to the data or to enforce regularization (to prevent overfitting).
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] There is a whole research branch dealing with all possible regularizations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] In practice, one usually tries a specific regularization and then figures out the probability density that corresponds to that regularization to justify the choice.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] It can also be physically motivated by common sense or intuition.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] In machine learning, the data term corresponds to the training data and the regularization is either the choice of the model or modifications to the algorithm.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] It is always intended to reduce the generalization error, i.e. the error score with the trained model on the evaluation set (testing data) and not the training data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] One of the earliest uses of regularization is Tikhonov regularization (ridge regression), related to the method of least squares.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] In machine learning, a key challenge is enabling models to accurately predict outcomes on unseen data, not just on familiar training data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Regularization is crucial for addressing overfitting—where a model memorizes training data details but cannot generalize to new data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The goal of regularization is to encourage models to learn the broader patterns within the data rather than memorizing it.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Techniques like early stopping, L1 and L2 regularization, and dropout are designed to prevent overfitting and underfitting, thereby enhancing the model's ability to adapt to and perform well with new data, thus improving model generalization.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Stops training when validation performance deteriorates, preventing overfitting by halting before the model memorizes training data.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] In the context of neural networks, the Dropout technique repeatedly ignores random subsets of neurons during training, which simulates the training of multiple neural network architectures at once to improve generalization.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Empirical learning of classifiers (from a finite data set) is always an underdetermined problem, because it attempts to infer a function of any x given only examples $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Concrete notions of complexity used include restrictions for smoothness and bounds on the vector space norm.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] A theoretical justification for regularization is that it attempts to impose Occam's razor on the solution (as depicted in the figure above, where the green function, the simpler one, may be preferred).
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] From a Bayesian point of view, many regularization techniques correspond to imposing certain prior distributions on model parameters.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Regularization can serve multiple purposes, including learning simpler models, inducing models to be sparse and introducing group structure into the learning problem.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The same idea arose in many fields of science.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] A simple form of regularization applied to integral equations (Tikhonov regularization) is essentially a trade-off between fitting the data and reducing a norm of the solution.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] More recently, non-linear regularization methods, including total variation regularization, have become popular.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Regularization can be motivated as a technique to improve the generalizability of a learned model.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The goal of this learning problem is to find a function that fits or predicts the outcome (label) that minimizes the expected error over all possible inputs and labels.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The expected error of a function $f_{n}$ is: $I[f_{n}]=\int _{X\times Y}V(f_{n}(x),y)\rho (x,y)\,dx\,dy$ where X and Y are the domains of input data x and their labels y respectively.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Typically in learning problems, only a subset of input data and labels are available, measured with some noise.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] If measurements (e.g. of $x_{i}$ ) were made with noise, this model may suffer from overfitting and display poor expected error.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Regularization introduces a penalty for exploring certain regions of the function space used to build the model, which can improve generalization.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] These techniques are named for Andrey Nikolayevich Tikhonov, who applied regularization to integral equations and made important contributions in many other areas.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] When learning a linear function f , characterized by an unknown vector w such that $f(x)=w\cdot x$ , one can add the $L_{2}$ -norm of the vector w to the loss expression in order to prefer solutions with smaller norms.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Tikhonov regularization is one of the most common forms.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] As the $L_{2}$ norm is differentiable, learning can be advanced by gradient descent.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The learning problem with the least squares loss function and Tikhonov regularization can be solved analytically.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] By construction of the optimization problem, other values of w give larger values for the loss function.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This can be verified by examining the second derivative $\nabla _{ww}$ .
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] During training, this algorithm takes $O(d^{3}+nd^{2})$ time.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The terms correspond to the matrix inversion and calculating $X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ , respectively.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Early stopping can be viewed as regularization in time.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Intuitively, a training procedure such as gradient descent tends to learn more and more complex functions with increasing iterations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] By regularizing for time, model complexity can be controlled, improving generalization.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Early stopping is implemented using one data set for training, one statistically independent data set for validation and another for testing.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The model is trained until performance on the validation set no longer improves and then applied to the test set.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The exact solution to the unregularized least squares learning problem minimizes the empirical error, but may fail.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] By limiting T, the only free parameter in the algorithm above, the problem is regularized for time, which may improve its generalization.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Enforcing a sparsity constraint on w can lead to simpler and more interpretable models.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This is useful in many real-life applications such as computational biology.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] An example is developing a simple predictive test for a disease in order to minimize the cost of performing medical tests while maximizing predictive power.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] A sensible sparsity constraint is the $L_{0}$ norm $\|w\|_{0}$ , defined as the number of non-zero elements in w .
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Solving a $L_{0}$ regularized learning problem, however, has been demonstrated to be NP-hard.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The $L_{1}$ norm (see also Norms) can be used to approximate the optimal $L_{0}$ norm via convex relaxation.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] It can be shown that the $L_{1}$ norm induces sparsity.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] $L_{1}$ regularization can occasionally produce non-unique solutions.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] A simple example is provided in the figure when the space of possible solutions lies on a 45 degree line.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Elastic net regularization tends to have a grouping effect, where correlated input features are assigned equal weights.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Elastic net regularization is commonly used in practice and is implemented in many machine learning libraries.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] While the $L_{1}$ norm does not result in an NP-hard problem, the $L_{1}$ norm is convex but is not strictly differentiable due to the kink at x = 0.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Subgradient methods which rely on the subderivative can be used to solve $L_{1}$ regularized learning problems.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] However, faster convergence can be achieved through proximal methods.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] For a problem $\min _{w\in H}F(w)+R(w)$ such that F is convex, continuous, differentiable, with Lipschitz continuous gradient (such as the least squares loss function), and R is convex, continuous, and proper, then the proximal method to solve the problem is as follows.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The proximal method iteratively performs gradient descent and then projects the result back into the space permitted by R .
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Groups of features can be regularized by a sparsity constraint, which can be useful for expressing certain prior knowledge into an optimization problem.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This can be viewed as inducing a regularizer over the $L_{2}$ norm over members of each group followed by an $L_{1}$ norm over groups.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The algorithm described for group sparsity without overlaps can be applied to the case where groups do overlap, in certain situations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This will likely result in some groups with all zero elements, and other groups with some non-zero and some zero elements.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] For each $w_{g}$ , ${\bar {w}}_{g}$ is defined as the vector such that the restriction of ${\bar {w}}_{g}$ to the group g equals $w_{g}$ and all other entries of ${\bar {w}}_{g}$ are zero.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The regularizer finds the optimal disintegration of w into parts.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] It can be viewed as duplicating all elements that exist in multiple groups.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Learning problems with this regularizer can also be solved with the proximal method with a complication.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The proximal operator cannot be computed in closed form, but can be effectively solved iteratively, inducing an inner iteration within the proximal method iteration.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] When labels are more expensive to gather than input examples, semi-supervised learning can be useful.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Regularizers have been designed to guide learning algorithms to learn models that respect the structure of unsupervised training samples.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] If $W_{ij}$ encodes the result of some distance metric for points $x_{i}$ and $x_{j}$ , it is desirable that $f(x_{i})\approx f(x_{j})$ .
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer captures this intuition, and is equivalent to: $R(f)={\bar {f}}^{\mathsf {T}}L{\bar {f}}$ where $L=D-W$ is the Laplacian matrix of the graph induced by W .
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The optimization problem $\min _{f\in \mathbb {R} ^{m}}R(f),m=u+l$ can be solved analytically if the constraint $f(x_{i})=y_{i}$ is applied for all supervised samples.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The labeled part of the vector f is therefore obvious.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] In the case of multitask learning, T problems are considered simultaneously, each related in some way.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The goal is to learn T functions, ideally borrowing strength from the relatedness of tasks, that have predictive power.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This is equivalent to learning the matrix $W:T\times D$ .
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer defines an L2 norm on each column and an L1 norm over all columns.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] $R(w)=\left\|\sigma (W)\right\|_{1}$ where $\sigma (W)$ is the eigenvalues in the singular value decomposition of W .
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer constrains the functions learned for each task to be similar to the overall average of the functions across all tasks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This is useful for expressing prior information that each task is expected to share with each other task.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] An example is predicting blood iron levels measured at different times of the day, where each task represents an individual.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This regularizer is similar to the mean-constrained regularizer, but instead enforces similarity between tasks within the same cluster.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This can capture more complex prior information.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] This technique has been used to predict Netflix recommendations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] A cluster would correspond to a group of people who share similar preferences.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] More generally than above, similarity between tasks can be defined by a function.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] The regularizer encourages the model to learn similar functions for similar tasks. $R(f_{1}\cdots f_{T})=\sum _{t,s=1,t\neq s}^{\mathsf {T}}\left\|f_{t}-f_{s}\right\|^{2}M_{ts}$ for a given symmetric similarity matrix M .
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Bayesian learning methods make use of a prior probability that (usually) gives lower probability to more complex models.
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Well-known model selection techniques include the Akaike information criterion (AIC), minimum description length (MDL), and the Bayesian information criterion (BIC).
[src:model-pruning-ml/regularization-mathematics] Alternative methods of controlling overfitting not involving regularization include cross-validation.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] In numerical analysis and scientific computing, a **sparse matrix** or **sparse array** is a matrix in which most of the elements are zero.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] There is no strict definition regarding the proportion of zero-value elements for a matrix to qualify as **sparse** but a common criterion is that the number of non-zero elements is roughly equal to the number of rows or columns.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] By contrast, if most of the elements are non-zero, the matrix is considered **dense**.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The number of zero-valued elements divided by the total number of elements (e.g., *m* × *n* for an *m* × *n* matrix) is sometimes referred to as the **sparsity** of the matrix.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Conceptually, sparsity corresponds to systems with few pairwise interactions.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] For example, consider a line of balls connected by springs from one to the next: this is a sparse system, as only adjacent balls are coupled.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] By contrast, if the same line of balls were to have springs connecting each ball to all other balls, the system would correspond to a dense matrix.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The concept of sparsity is useful in combinatorics and application areas such as network theory and numerical analysis, which typically have a low density of significant data or connections.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Large sparse matrices often appear in scientific or engineering applications when solving partial differential equations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] When storing and manipulating sparse matrices on a computer, it is beneficial and often necessary to use specialized algorithms and data structures that take advantage of the sparse structure of the matrix.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Specialized computers have been made for sparse matrices, as they are common in the machine learning field.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Operations using standard dense-matrix structures and algorithms are slow and inefficient when applied to large sparse matrices as processing and memory are wasted on the zeros.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Sparse data is by nature more easily compressed and thus requires significantly less storage.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Some very large sparse matrices are infeasible to manipulate using standard dense-matrix algorithms.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The band matrices form a special class of sparse matrix where the non-zero elements are concentrated near the main diagonal.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] A band matrix is characterised by its lower and upper bandwidths, which refer to the number of diagonals below and above (respectively) the main diagonal between which all of the non-zero entries are contained.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Formally, the lower bandwidth of a matrix **A** is the smallest number *p* such that the entry *a**i*,*j* vanishes whenever *i* > *j* + *p*.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Similarly, the upper bandwidth is the smallest number *p* such that *a**i*,*j* = 0 whenever *i* < *j* − *p* (Golub & Van Loan 1996, §1.2.1).
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] For example, a tridiagonal matrix has lower bandwidth 1 and upper bandwidth 1.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] As another example, the following sparse matrix has lower and upper bandwidth both equal to 3.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Matrices with reasonably small upper and lower bandwidth are known as band matrices and often lend themselves to simpler algorithms than general sparse matrices; or one can sometimes apply dense matrix algorithms and gain efficiency simply by looping over a reduced number of indices.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] By rearranging the rows and columns of a matrix **A** it may be possible to obtain a matrix **A**′ with a lower bandwidth.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] A number of algorithms are designed for bandwidth minimization.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] A diagonal matrix is the extreme case of a band matrix, with zero upper and lower bandwidth.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] A diagonal matrix can be stored efficiently by storing just the entries in the main diagonal as a one-dimensional array, so a diagonal *n* × *n* matrix requires only *n* entries in memory.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] A symmetric sparse matrix arises as the adjacency matrix of an undirected graph; it can be stored efficiently as an adjacency list.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] A block-diagonal matrix consists of sub-matrices along its diagonal blocks.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The *fill-in* of a matrix are those entries that change from an initial zero to a non-zero value during the execution of an algorithm.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] To reduce the memory requirements and the number of arithmetic operations used during an algorithm, it is useful to minimize the fill-in by switching rows and columns in the matrix.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The symbolic Cholesky decomposition can be used to calculate the worst possible fill-in before doing the actual Cholesky decomposition.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] There are other methods than the Cholesky decomposition in use.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Orthogonalization methods (such as QR factorization) are common, for example, when solving problems by least squares methods.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] While the theoretical fill-in is still the same, in practical terms the "false non-zeros" can be different for different methods.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] And symbolic versions of those algorithms can be used in the same manner as the symbolic Cholesky to compute worst case fill-in.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Both iterative and direct methods exist for sparse matrix solving.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Iterative methods, such as conjugate gradient method and GMRES utilize fast computations of matrix-vector products $Ax_{i}$ , where matrix A is sparse.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The use of preconditioners can significantly accelerate convergence of such iterative methods.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] A matrix is typically stored as a two-dimensional array.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Each entry in the array represents an element *a**i*,*j* of the matrix and is accessed by the two indices *i* and *j*.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Conventionally, *i* is the row index, numbered from top to bottom, and *j* is the column index, numbered from left to right.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] For an *m* × *n* matrix, the amount of memory required to store the matrix in this format is proportional to *m* × *n* (disregarding the fact that the dimensions of the matrix also need to be stored).
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] In the case of a sparse matrix, substantial memory requirement reductions can be realized by storing only the non-zero entries.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Depending on the number and distribution of the non-zero entries, different data structures can be used and yield huge savings in memory when compared to the basic approach.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The trade-off is that accessing the individual elements becomes more complex and additional structures are needed to be able to recover the original matrix unambiguously.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] DOK consists of a dictionary that maps (row, column)-pairs to the value of the elements.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Elements that are missing from the dictionary are taken to be zero.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The format is good for incrementally constructing a sparse matrix in random order, but poor for iterating over non-zero values in lexicographical order.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] One typically constructs a matrix in this format and then converts to another more efficient format for processing.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] LIL stores one list per row, with each entry containing the column index and the value.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Typically, these entries are kept sorted by column index for faster lookup.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] This is another format good for incremental matrix construction.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] COO stores a list of (row, column, value) tuples.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Ideally, the entries are sorted first by row index and then by column index, to improve random access times.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] This is another format that is good for incremental matrix construction.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The *compressed sparse row* (CSR) or *compressed row storage* (CRS) or Yale format represents a matrix **M** by three (one-dimensional) arrays, that respectively contain nonzero values, the extents of rows, and column indices.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] It is similar to COO, but compresses the row indices, hence the name.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] This format allows fast row access and matrix-vector multiplications (**M***x*).
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The CSR format has been in use since at least the mid-1960s, with the first complete description appearing in 1967.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The CSR format stores a sparse *m* × *n* matrix **M** in row form using three (one-dimensional) arrays (V, COL_INDEX, ROW_INDEX).
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Let NNZ denote the number of nonzero entries in **M**.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Then we take slices from V and COL_INDEX starting at row_start and ending at row_end.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] To extract the row 1 (the second row) of this matrix we set `row_start=1` and `row_end=2`.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] We now know that in row 1 we have one element at column 1 with value 8.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] In this case the CSR representation contains 13 entries, compared to 16 in the original matrix.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The CSR format saves on memory only when NNZ < (*m* (*n* − 1) − 1) / 2.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The whole is stored as 21 entries: 8 in V, 8 in COL_INDEX, and 5 in ROW_INDEX.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Note that in this format, the first value of ROW_INDEX is always zero and the last is always NNZ, so they are in some sense redundant (although in programming languages where the array length needs to be explicitly stored, NNZ would not be redundant).
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Nonetheless, this does avoid the need to handle an exceptional case when computing the length of each row, as it guarantees the formula ROW_INDEX[*i* + 1] − ROW_INDEX[*i*] works for any row *i*.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Moreover, the memory cost of this redundant storage is likely insignificant for a sufficiently large matrix.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The (old and new) Yale sparse matrix formats are instances of the CSR scheme.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The old Yale format works exactly as described above, with three arrays; the new format combines ROW_INDEX and COL_INDEX into a single array and handles the diagonal of the matrix separately.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] For logical adjacency matrices, the data array can be omitted, as the existence of an entry in the row array is sufficient to model a binary adjacency relation.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] It is likely known as the Yale format because it was proposed in the 1977 Yale Sparse Matrix Package report from Department of Computer Science at Yale University.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] CSC is similar to CSR except that values are read first by column, a row index is stored for each value, and column pointers are stored.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] For example, CSC is (val, row_ind, col_ptr), where val is an array of the (top-to-bottom, then left-to-right) non-zero values of the matrix; row_ind is the row indices corresponding to the values; and, col_ptr is the list of val indexes where each column starts.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The name is based on the fact that column index information is compressed relative to the COO format.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] One typically uses another format (LIL, DOK, COO) for construction.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] This format is efficient for arithmetic operations, column slicing, and matrix-vector products.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] This is the traditional format for specifying a sparse matrix in MATLAB (via the `sparse` function).
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] Many software libraries support sparse matrices, and provide solvers for sparse matrix equations.
[src:model-pruning-ml/sparse-matrix] The term *sparse matrix* was possibly coined by Harry Markowitz who initiated some pioneering work but then left the field.
